5000|$|Line-drawing {{would be}} {{impossible}} to do in a principled way. [...] "Public policy comes in many variations, is implicated in many contexts, and is carried out by many people, both publicly and privately. Once expanded in the manner argued here, the <b>public</b> <b>policy</b> <b>exception</b> would no longer be subject to any discernable limiting principles. It would arguably apply to retaliatory discharges based upon the conduct of any non-employee relative, for the fulfillment of or refusal to violate public policy {{in a wide variety of}} ways and in a manner completely unconnected to the employment relationship. The <b>public</b> <b>policy</b> <b>exception</b> cannot be stretched that far and still be recognizable under Brockmeyer's limited formulation." ...|$|E
